Parliamentary practice in a time of pandemic: updating you on the response from Parliaments around the world.

The Parliament of Montenegro is holding a combination of remote and face-to-face meetings; utilising Zoom & Cisco Webex where necessary. Over the past two months, the Parliament continued to meet physically, but with appropriate social distancing and medical preventive measures in place in all parliamentary rooms. There were fewer parliamentarians present in the plenary room, and all necessary medical preventive measures were taken, including disinfection, and wearing protective face masks and gloves. 
How is your Parliament coping with the pandemic? Keep up to date with our country compilation of parliamentary responses to the pandemic live at ipu.org.

node.text:
CONTINUES... Forty percent. (These are people who had positive nose swabs but stay completely asymptomatic.)
FORTY PERCENT! It’s awesome that four out of ten people don’t suffer from the disease at all, don’t have long-term sequelae, etc.
But it also means four out of ten people who have Covid have absolutely no idea they are infected, don’t know they’re contagious, don’t realize that every time they speak/yell/cough/sneeze they may be spewing tons of infected confetti all over the place, don’t know they may be an actual danger to family and friends.
But if they're wearing a mask, they’re not so dangerous.
There is now a good amount of research, old and new, showing masks filter out the majority of viral particles. All masks matter, to varying degrees. Without getting into a song and dance about the exact numbers, here’s the basics:
•	N95s are better than surgical masks
•	cloth masks are way better than nothing
•	two masks (one on me, one on you) are better than one
•	having it on your chin doesn’t work
Masks can work to protect other people from your infection.
and
Masks can work to protect you from other people’s infection.
and furthermore
•	Masks can work to protect you from getting ANY virus inside you.
•	Masks can protect you from getting LOTS of virus inside of you.
You always need a certain amount of viruses spewed at you like the above mentioned confetti to get sick. It can’t be just one solo virus — it has to be thousands. Masks have been shown to cut those numbers down.
Even better, there is evidence that the volume of virus that gets into your mouth or nose is related to how sick you get. So when you wear a mask and hang out with people wearing masks, early studies seem to indicate you are increasing your chances of having milder disease. (...)

CONTINUES... It even appears that masking increases the rates of being asymptomatic! In some very interesting early studies, we are seeing this happen. It’s happened on cruise ships, it’s happened in food processing plants — even in the midst of big outbreaks, infected people who use masks are more likely to be completely without symptoms.
When we don’t wear masks, we have more deaths. We saw this so tragically in Italy and New York among health care workers.
When you do have places mostly masking (eg >80%) you may well see fewer deaths. San Francisco (a great masking place, like Boston) has had ONE death since July 16 despite 1500 new cases. And deaths have stayed low post-surge in the Far East countries where masking is part of the cultural norm and most countries where masking had been mandatory.
This is not to say that masking is a miracle cure-all; we still need physical distancing and hand washing and staying home when sick.
Still, what a lot of reasons to wear a mask:
— you don’t have to walk around with the guilt of being Patient Zero
— you have less chance of getting it
— you probably have a higher chance of being asymptomatic
— you may well have less chance of getting super sick
— you may have less chance of dying of it
And you won't make your doctor burst into tears in the middle of a presentation."
I unfortunately do not agree with this statement. Love your eye color though 🙌

"Today I’m talking about how Masks May Be Magic.
Massachusetts is still okay, trending up a bit in terms of numbers of cases but hospitals are fine, deaths are low.
The rest of the US outside of the Northeast: it’s just unspeakable. The numbers are unfathomable.
How bad is it?
Here’s an analogy:
More or less, the US is having one Wuhan a day. Remember how terrible Wuhan was and ended up being? That many cases are happening every day in the US.
Here’s some statistics:
How fast are cases exploding?
0 cases to 1 million cases: 98 days
1 million to 2 million cases: 44 days
2 million to 3 million cases: 27 days
3 million to 4 million cases: 14 days
Here’s a story:
Every Thursday night I listen to this whiz kid Infectious Disease doc from Texas talk about Covid. She talks non-stop for an hour and whips through about 55 papers, summarizing study after study after study. She’s like the kid in high school who was absolutely the smartest person in the room and made it look easy; she’s amazing. 
At a recent broadcast she was quoting a paper and all of a sudden she started crying. I couldn’t even figure out what was happening (I was doing dishes in my Eternal Multitasking Fashion) but when I stopped loading the dishwasher and looked at my computer screen, there she was, wiping her eyes and weeping. That’s what life is like in Texas.
In the midst of this misery, let’s talk about something positive. Let’s talk about masks.
I love masks. Right now they feel like are like our magic protectors, like holding garlic up in front of Dracula, or wearing a special amulet that keeps the evil eye away.
Or maybe like wearing a condom and not getting syphilis.
Why are masks particularly important with Covid?
Well, as with Everything Covid, “we are building the plane while we fly it.” We are accumulating data as fast as we can and some trends look promising. While some of this may change over time, for now this is what we know.
First off, it appears, unbelievably, that the rate of people who are infected but have no symptoms is around 40% (...)

For me it’s been all about healing. Healing internally on a physical and emotional level. Connecting with my higher self💖.

Many of you have reported to me that you also experienced the 6th stage of Grief …” “finding meaning”... through this Pandemic. 

For me, the 6th stage (finding meaning) revolved around having a successful Telemedicine 👩‍💻 practice from the comfort of my home office which allowed me to reduce my carbon footprint 👣 and spend more time with family. 

I discovered mountain biking 🚵‍♀️ for fitness and to keep me grounded and thriving.  Apparently I’m not alone in this...as the trails have been super busy 🤩 and bike stock and supplies are almost non existent due to the demand.

I also found the perfect 🤩 “partner in crime” @meetmarywong to do our podcast 🎙 series called @embrace_me_first launching August 18th 2020. 

🌟Please share with me. 👇🏻Comment below. 👇🏻Have you found meaning in all this?  Have you experienced the 6th stage of grief?  Note: the stages of grief are not linear and it’s completely normal to hop from one stage to another as our lives are forever changed.

@jess.everafter Thank you! Oh gosh I hope it went okay! They’re moving from Maryland to Florida so it’s been crazy hard to coordinate everything from a far so we finally just had to come down.
It’s such a weird time right now, we had to move during it too. It’s crazy for sure. I hope your dad recovers quickly!
It really is such a crazy time! Hoping for an easy move for your parents and that your dad heals quickly!!

Happy Monday! Olive and I are here in the Villages helping my mom get moved in while my dad recovers from surgery back home. We’ve had a crazy few weeks, but we’ve all had a crazy 2020. My parents had planned to move to the Villages this summer since last year. Turns out when you buy a house, the seller doesn’t care if there’s a pandemic 😂. I’ve been sharing lots of photos of our very long car ride down in my stories and some of the gorgeous views from our golf cart rides. We came across this sign last night and I snapped a quick photo. This trip was definitely not what we’d dreamed of when this process started. We planned to spend a long time, see and do lots of things, travel around Florida, and my dad should be here too. Instead it was super stressful trying to safely drive down 😷, we had to go to the grocery store for food (sounds crazy but I haven’t been in a store since February), and just hang out at the house while movers and other repair people run in and out in masks. I say all this because my parents dream of retiring and moving to Florida did come true, it just doesn’t look the way it should right now. It’s been really hard on all of us, giving up our dreams right now, but when I saw this sign it made me realize there’s still hope all our dreams can come true when this is all over. Stay safe everyone ❤️

node.text: Lovely make up and hair do
Lovely make up and hair do

It’s almost August - and in an almost surreptitious manner, the second half of the year has arrived! For a lot of us, we’ve reached the end of our rope and for some (me included!) we feel
CAGED! 

There! I said it. 

The routine of waking up to another day of 24683537 tasks that lie ahead of me along with figuring out ways to entertain my extremely hyper children has me very thinly spread out and has also proved to be endemic to some of my closest relationships. And that’s saying a LOT! I feel trapped. Caged in my own misery! 

But caged is such a strong word! Yes, I’m indoors more than ever and I don’t get to do as much as I’d like to - but, I’m safe and I’m healthy! 

It’s ultimately the little things that matter. The things we take for granted. The things that get overlooked in all of the hustle and though this pandemic has proven costly to so many of us, an attitude of gratitude is what makes this journey bearable! 

It’s #onedayatatime from now on! 
.
.
.

So, there are key factors to look at when disputing collection accounts— ✨ .
.
First off, What is a Collections? Lets look at this logically 🧐 A collection is an account that was due at one point in time that did not get paid by You, the consumer, after being late for a specific period of time. By DEFAULT, it's already late📌 Therefore, there should be no late payments reported in the payment history of the account. 
A collection should not state “120 days late”. The ORIGINAL account may state 120 days, 150 days or 180 days/charged-off. However, it should not report in the least on a collection. Pay close attention to This!! Creditors often times mess up here!

So when disputing a collection, you will want to ensure that you're looking at all elements of the account and not just stating that it's "unknown" or "unverified". But find FACTUAL inaccurate information and hone in on that. 💕 Learn more at Www.thirtygirl.org

node.text:
There are so many things going on that threaten to tear us apart--in our world, our country, and our personal lives. 

And it's so easy to let those things consume us and encourage us to fuel the fire of division, anger, and conflict. 

If I let these things take control of my thoughts and actions, it will hinder my ability to serve my clients, my colleagues, and my family or friends.

What if we focused more on the things that are holding us together? 

One thing hasn't changed: we're STILL all in this together!

Let's use that truth to fight against those things that are tearing us apart.

node.text:
A virtual conference doesn’t require attendees to travel, which means they don’t have to pay for hotel and logistics, this allows international attendance to go up. This platform allows content to be easily recorded, which means it can be repurposed at a later date which could be a new revenue stream via Video On-Demand. A lot of people attend conferences for the networking opportunities and hallway conversations that take place.  Access to a live chat with a keynoter, small breakout-rooms, Q&As with your board chair or CEO allows seemless networking opportunity to the participants. 

In turn you get precise and more accurate Data collection when you host a virtual conference. Such activations let you know exactly who your audience is and what they do. You can gather data in Real-Time and use it in a number of creative ways to make your event much more useful for the attendees by fulfilling their needs on the go.

Contact @whitemagicmedia for all your event curation needs !

Any how I was looking for someone who can satisfy my urgent kheer craving crisis and guess what? I found this lady from @andsneverend who takes order for kheer. I kid you not guys! node.text:
A very special hamper, in these special times. We’ve all dealt with Covid-19 in our own ways, no matter where we’ve been in the world. Fears that we were not aware of, situations we were never prepared for, dealing with a threat that was invisible and silent. The fragility of life just became more frail. Not only for me, but for everyone. And in these times, Dettol was a name that was part of my life and my home. The reassurance that these products provided safety for me and my family when used with proper practice, took me a long way. I received this Eid hamper just yesterday and these past 4 months flashed before my eyes. The loss of family members due to the virus, hearing first hand experiences from loved ones, struggling with the ever building anxiety and panic levels, the helplessness... nevertheless, it also took me back to the times of hope, of health, of repeated positive affirmations, of the capabilities we never knew we had to help us fight and get past the craziest of times. Thank you for this Eid basket, this truly is a hifazat hamper

Barefoot and making pregnancy during a pandemic look much easier than it actually is.
.
.
As grateful as I am for this baby girl on the way, this pregnancy has been just as weird and challenging as the rest of 2020. After starting of the new year with a stomach bug on top of pregnancy nausea (thanks to my toddler for that gem), COVID hit and turned the world upside down. 
.
.
For those of us who have been pregnant lately, that’s meant tackling a lot of this pregnancy stuff alone. My husband couldn’t come to the 20 week ultrasound and didn’t even hear the baby’s heartbeat until 31 weeks. My son hasn’t been allowed to a single appointment and won’t be able to visit at the hospital when his sister is born. 
.
.
For me personally, it’s meant being diagnosed with melanoma (yes, as in skin cancer) in the 2nd trimester and being alone while having to get a procedure to remove it- since it was during a time when we were fully quarantining and my husband had to stay home with our son. (Thankfully, it was caught early and the cancer is gone!) It also meant losing a grandparent in the 3rd trimester and not being able to go to the funeral or be with my family because of the number of people that would be there without masks on (on top of the travel to get there.)
.
.
Now, while COVID cases are spiking in our area, my pregnancy is high risk, which means I’m at the doctors and hospital 3x a week for tests and weekly ultrasounds. And I’m terrified of getting COVID prior to getting tested for delivery. 
.
.
I share all of this not for sympathy but in case there are others going through similarly weird and challenging things during this pandemic- you’re not alone! ALSO, if I can manage tons of doctor and hospital visits with a mask on- all while having trouble breathing at times because of an excess amount of fluid putting pressure on my lungs- you can wear a mask to buy your groceries without complaining. The End. 

#wearamask #36weekspregnant #quarantinehair #pandemic2020 
📸: @valerie.demo

Cut that in half so you basically have 1/4 of the plate x2 and then stitch the two curved edges together - these would form the part that goes over the nose and mouth. The pointy bits you’re left with can be cut off to make the mask the correct size x

node.text:
Meet Irina. @pedicure_plus has been providing a huge list of beauty treatments in Kingston for years. ‘When we shut during lockdown it was a scary time, we were worried about whether we would even be allowed to reopen so when the news came we could we were so excited to come back. We all wear face shields and masks. There is sanitizer everywhere and we clean each station after a customer. The reaction since we reopened has been amazing. I have had clients skipping out because they’ve been so happy to come and get their nails done. We just really, really hope there isn’t a second spike, like all the other businesses around here we need to make money to survive and we’re working as hard as we can to make sure everyone is safe as can be in the salon. When we opened our email system to check for pre-booking we had over a thousand enquiries. It was 
amazing and we’ve been so busy ever since, we just hope it stays that way.

Video by Human Health Research !!! in Pennington Biomedical Research Center. Image may contain: text that says 'Diet Obesity MS BMI OBESITY NOW GLOBAL EPIDEMIC! Obesity throatandther tolungs @sci_exploraaa'. Hormone reveals why COVID-19 is dangerous for people with obesity

Researchers have stumbled upon a hormone that connects the body’s metabolism and immune response system and can explain why COVID-19 is so dangerous for people with obesity.

published in the International Journal of Obesity.

1) The hormone leptin regulates appetite and metabolism. It also regulates the cells that fight infection.

2) Leptin is produced by fat cells and, to a lesser extent, by tissues in the lungs. The more fat a person has, the more leptin circulates in their body.

3) “The problem for people with obesity is that their leptin levels are always high, and that can affect the response to a COVID-19 infection”. 

4) Elevated leptin levels hamper the body’s ability to fight off infections, in the lungs and elsewhere.

5) High leptin levels promote a low-grade systemic inflammatory state.

6) “If you have obesity, there are a number of underlying health issues that make it more difficult for you to fight off a COVID-19 infection”.

7) Your entire body, including your lungs, may be inflamed. Your immune response is likely compromised, and your lung capacity reduced.

8) Add in a virus that further weakens the body’s ability to fight infection, that can limit the body's ability to control lung inflammation, and you have the recipe for disaster.

9) COVID-19 vaccine developers should take the immune-compromised state resulting from obesity into consideration, in much the same way they would advancing age.

#obesity #fightingobesity #obesitykills #obesityepidemic #obesitysurvivor #pandemic #pandemic2020 #covid19 #pennington #biomedicalresearch #researcher #vaccinemaker

node.text: Vacation at home, as the pandemy has killed all official motor events, this summer has sucked for real. Some days I think that I will loose it for real If this lockdown limitations continues. All I want is one single bike run and a good old bike show to go with it. Like the ones that car people arrange when they go for their ”non organized” ice cream runs in the city center... But at least, this weekends evening walk with my camera turned in to something like strange postcards of my home town... node.text:
#Repost @imake_thing (@get_repost)
・・・
The coronavirus pandemic has affected people in very different ways. Some are struggling to cope, while others want to calm down and get back to business as usual. So, as companies navigate a slow return to ordinary life and work routines, leaders must understand that employees will need varying kinds of support. This is not a time to robotically “copy all” with messages about thoughts and prayers, but a time to help each individual with their unique grief. Most of all, it’s important to provide the space for healing by allowing people to feel what they’re going through.

Here are two approaches to consider when helping employees emerge from the crisis:

Find the right interventions. Avoid blanket policies; not all employees need the same support. Some may be grieving the loss of normalcy or dealing with anxiety about the future; for them, working might help them balance out their thoughts. Others, like those who have been sick or have cared for sick family members or friends, have gone through a traumatic experience and may need validation or even counseling. Thinking about the different possibilities can help you tailor support to each person’s needs.

Support the search for meaning. People may struggle to move on from their grief if they’re having a hard time seeing the purpose behind their pain. But finding meaning doesn’t always happen during a crisis. It could happen in the aftermath and it could come in many forms. For example, remembering the joy that came with something or someone before it was lost could bring meaning. Some may take comfort in expressing gratitude or finding small moments that heal. 

Because we’re all going through this pandemic together, it’s possible that we may find meaning and heal sooner than we would from most losses. But healing doesn’t mean that the pandemic was worth it or that we’ll forget the damages done — it means that the damages no longer control our outlook on life.
—

ПСИХОЛОГИЧЕСКАЯ ДРАММА 
«утро понедельника» -во всех домах страны ☀️

К понедельникам можно относиться по-разному. Одни считают этот день самым тяжелым, другие же, напротив, полагают, что начало новой недели, как новое окно возможностей.
Негативное отношение к понедельнику существовало с давних времен. Так как у христиан воскресный день был нерабочим, то понедельник, понятное дело, особой популярностью не пользовался. С глобализацией же по всему миру распространилась так называемая «английская неделя» с двумя нерабочими днями — субботой и воскресеньем. И понедельнику вновь приходится «отдуваться». 
Так что понедельник, жаль как пчела 🐝 порхай как бабочка 🦋
